{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1774546547,"nonce":"mT3biX0yZ2/CjqmcSr5TbemTrsE=","message":"**Tier 1 results summary (2026-03-26)**\n\nAll three Tier 1 approaches produce 0.00% SISU velocity effect at batch 499 checkpoint:\n\n| Approach | Architecture | Adversary | vel(S=0) | vel(S=1) | Δvel% |\n|----------|-------------|-----------|----------|----------|-------|\n| A: ratio=0.3 | GRU (additive) | single | 0.5519±0.10 | 0.5519±0.10 | 0.00% |\n| A: ratio=0.3 | GRU (additive) | pop K=5 | 0.5414±0.06 | 0.5414±0.06 | 0.00% |\n| C: vanilla RNN | LeakyRNN (additive) | single | 0.4245±0.06 | 0.4245±0.06 | 0.00% |\n| C: vanilla RNN | LeakyRNN (additive) | pop K=5 | 0.4008±0.06 | 0.4008±0.06 | 0.00% |\n| B: mult gating | GRU (multiplicative) | single | 0.8355±0.14 | 0.8355±0.14 | 0.00% |\n| B: mult gating | GRU (multiplicative) | pop K=5 | 0.8714±0.15 | 0.8714±0.15 | 0.00% |\n\nKey observations:\n1. Multiplicative gating produces FASTER reaching (0.84) vs additive GRU (0.55) vs vanilla RNN (0.42)\n2. Population-based adversary does NOT improve SISU sensitivity vs single adversary\n3. Removing GRU gating (vanilla RNN) does NOT produce SISU effect — rules out gating-laziness hypothesis\n4. Multiplicative SISU modulation of hidden state does NOT produce SISU effect — SISU gain modulation is not sufficient\n\nConclusion: The problem is not in the input pathway (additive vs multiplicative), not in the gating mechanism (GRU vs vanilla RNN), and not in the adversary diversity (single vs population). The issue appears fundamental to the optimization landscape — under minimax training, the optimal policy is SISU-independent regardless of how SISU enters the network.","files":null}]}